Loading and tuning Redshift: COPY, Spectrum, and distribution and sort keys.

The right way to bulk-load Redshift is the copy command. It reads files in parallel from S3, with each compute-node slice pulling its own files, it supports C-S-V, J-SON, Parquet, O-R-C, and Avro, and it's orders of magnitude faster than insert statements. The pattern in almost every Redshift pipeline is: land the data in S3, then copy it into the warehouse. Redshift Spectrum is the other half of the S3 story: it lets Redshift query data directly in S3 without loading it first. You define external tables backed by S3 objects, usually cataloged in the Glue Data Catalog, and standard Redshift S-Q-L can join those external tables against tables inside the cluster. Spectrum spins up its own pool of nodes to scan S3 in parallel, billed per terabyte scanned. The split is useful: hot, frequently-joined data lives inside Redshift, and cold historical data stays in S3 and is queried via Spectrum when needed.

Two physical-design choices govern performance on large tables. Distribution style decides how rows are placed across the compute nodes. AUTO lets Redshift choose based on table size, and it's the default. KEY hashes a column so equal values land on the same node, which is right for large tables joined frequently on that column. ALL puts a full copy of the table on every node, which is right for small dimension tables joined a lot. And EVEN is round-robin, for when there's no clear join key. A classic pattern: a large orders fact table distributed KEY on customer-I-D, with the small customers dimension table distributed ALL, so the join runs locally on each node with no network shuffle.

Sort keys decide the order data is stored within each node. Redshift keeps zone maps, recording the min and max value per block, so a filter on the sort key can skip blocks that can't possibly match, massively cutting I/O for range-filtered and time-series queries.
